&ldquo;Ariana Grande didn&rsquo;t have to put out a second album, Thank U, Next, just months after her Grammy-winning 2018 project Sweetener. But she did, and at one point in February held all three top spots on the Billboard Hot 100 chart &mdash; the first artist to do so since the Beatles. Her success was buoyed, in part, by hype she built via Twitter call-outs that doubled as song lyrics and music videos designed for (and steeped in) internet culture, including a Mean Girls-inspired concept for the album&rsquo;s title track. It helps, of course, that Grande recently became Instagram&rsquo;s most-followed musician, giving her an even bigger platform (223 million followers across Instagram and Twitter) to promote her work. &mdash;Raisa Bruner&rdquo;
